[SPEAKER_19]: Outcome-based budgeting, as opposed to the more traditional line-item incremental budgeting where expenditures are increased or decreased by a percentage from prior year levels, outcome-based budgeting is unique in that it ties in strategic planning,

1081
01:49:28,158 --> 01:49:29,319
[SPEAKER_19]: Performance management.

1082
01:49:30,680 --> 01:49:42,110
[SPEAKER_19]: Outcome-based budgeting requires the mayor and department heads to develop an improved set of government priorities for the coming year, such as enhanced public safety or increased economic development.

1083
01:49:42,691 --> 01:49:48,355
[SPEAKER_19]: These larger priorities then cascade down through the departments and permeate each of their own annual work plans.

1084
01:49:48,836 --> 01:49:54,581
[SPEAKER_19]: Resources are then calibrated toward the specific activities that are designed to realize those outcomes.

1085
01:49:55,310 --> 01:49:59,922
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, I think that's exactly what we as a council have been talking about for years.

1086
